40|$|In this paper, {{the authors}} examine {{the role of}} {{backwardation}} {{in the performance of}} passive <b>long</b> <b>positions</b> in soybeans, corn and wheat futures over the period of 1950 to 2004. They find that over this period, backwardation has been highly predictive of the return of a passive <b>long</b> futures <b>position</b> when measured over long investment horizons. The share of return variance explained by backwardation rises from 24 % at a one-year horizon to 64 % using five-year time periods. A historical examination of soybean production and trading suggests that the profitability of a passive <b>long</b> soybean <b>position</b> during the early part of their sample may have resulted from inadequate inventories and storage facilities at the time. These conditions created the conditions for demand-driven price spikes. Further, the thin margins of soybean processors likely increased hedging demand. The implications for commodity investing are considered...|$|R
